[3
Date: Sun, 30 Jan 2000 14:49:03 -0600
From: David W. Beasley <dwbeasle@utmb.edu>
I was recently contacted by an Australian who had returned from Bangladesh
in early December 1999 with reported symptoms and serology indicative of
mild dengue haemorrhagic fever. From the reported history, this was
apparently a secondary infection and the infecting serotype was not clear
from the ELISA and HAI results.
--
David Beasley
Postdoctoral Fellow
Center for Tropical Diseases and Department of Pathology
University of Texas Medical Branch
Galveston TX USA
e-mail: dwbeasle@utmb.edu
[In sum, we still have no data, only vague reports. Still, dengue and
dengue hemorrhagic fever in a country as densely population as is
Bangladesh is a situation to be taken very seriously. At this time,
control is more important that serotype determination. - Mod.CHC
